      <div class="card has-background-primary has-text-light" data-tag-collapse data-tags="composition, system_design">
        <div class="card-image">
          <figure class="image is-16by9">
            <iframe class="has-ratio" src="{{ projects.exodus_burned.embed }}" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
          </figure>
        </div>

        <div class="card-content">
          <h3 class="has-text-light">Exodus Burned</h3>

          <div class="tags">
            <span class="tag is-dark">Composition</span>
            <span class="tag is-dark">System design</span>
          </div>

          <p>In 2018 and 2019 I did a technical audio design internship at <i>Pillow's Willow VR Studios</i>. During this internship I worked on sound effects, voice overs and audio flow and implementation for <i>Exodus Burned</i>, a multiplayer VR experience, where players use their whole body as a controller to complete challenges. All audio integration work was done in Unity and C#.</p>
          <p>In 2020 I composed the music for their intro cinematic as well, for which I took inspiration from the epic orchestral music of <i>Two Steps From Hell</i>.</p>

          <div class="buttons">
            <a class="button is-link is-inverted" href="{{ projects.exodus_burned.link }}">
              <span class="icon is-small"><i class="fas fa-link"></i></span>
              <span>Visit website</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card has-background-primary has-text-light" data-tag-collapse data-tags="system_design, paper">
        <div class="card-content">
          <h3 class="has-text-light">Audio integration in Unity</h3>

          <div class="tags">
            <span class="tag is-dark">System design</span>
            <span class="tag is-dark">Paper</span>
          </div>

          <p>In this (Dutch) article is discussed how nonlinear music can be implemented in a game using and building upon the audio components of the Unity game engine,</p>

